Item 11 — Code of Ethics, Participation or Interest in Client Transactions and Personal Trading

The firm has adopted a Code of Ethics in accordance with Rule 204A-1 of the Investment Advisers Act and the requirements applicable to the firm as a subsidiary of a national bank. All access persons of the firm are required to:

1. Acknowledge receipt and review of the Code of Ethics annually;
2. Submit annual personal holdings reports;
3. Submit quarterly personal transaction reports;
4. Pre-clear all personal transactions in any reportable security other than transactions in shares of registered open-end investment companies (other than the Cornerstone Funds, which require pre-clearance), exchange-traded funds, money market instruments, and direct obligations of the U.S. government;
5. Comply with a 60-day holding period for personal transactions in any individual equity security; and
6. Refrain from personal transactions in any security on the firm's restricted list.

The firm and its supervised persons may invest in the same securities recommended to clients. As described in Item 10 above, the firm's recommendation of Cornerstone Funds presents a material conflict of interest because the firm receives compensation from such recommendations.

A copy of the firm's Code of Ethics is available to clients and prospective clients upon request.
